</div><img src="http://feeds.feedburner.com/~r/boundlessline/blog/~4/ecCOIS-UZlE" height="1" width="1"/>";s:7:"attribs";a:0:{}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";}}s:8:"category";a:2:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:"data";s:5:"faith";s:7:"attribs";a:1:{s:0:"";a:1:{s:6:"domain";s:81:"http://community.focusonthefamily.com/b/boundless/archive/tags/faith/default.aspx";}}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";}i:1;a:5:{s:4:"data";s:6:"career";s:7:"attribs";a:1:{s:0:"";a:1:{s:6:"domain";s:82:"http://community.focusonthefamily.com/b/boundless/archive/tags/career/default.aspx";}}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";}}}s:32:"http://purl.org/dc/elements/1.1/";a:1:{s:7:"creator";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:"data";s:8:"Amy Seed";s:7:"attribs";a:0:{}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";}}}s:38:"http://purl.org/rss/1.0/modules/slash/";a:1:{s:8:"comments";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:"data";s:1:"0";s:7:"attribs";a:0:{}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";}}}s:36:"http://wellformedweb.org/CommentAPI/";a:1:{s:10:"commentRss";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:"data";s:84:"http://community.focusonthefamily.com/b/boundless/rsscomments.aspx?WeblogPostID=6123";s:7:"attribs";a:0:{}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";}}}s:42:"http://rssnamespace.org/feedburner/ext/1.0";a:1:{s:8:"origLink";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:"data";s:94:"http://community.focusonthefamily.com/b/boundless/archive/2013/07/17/when-things-go-wrong.aspx";s:7:"attribs";a:0:{}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";}}}}}i:3;a:6:{s:4:"data";s:0:"";s:7:"attribs";a:0:{}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";s:5:"child";a:5:{s:0:"";a:7:{s:5:"title";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:"data";s:37:"Is Early Marriage Really a Good Idea?";s:7:"attribs";a:0:{}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";}}s:4:"link";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:"data";s:102:"http://feedproxy.google.com/~r/boundlessline/blog/~3/-5oOU40eO3U/the-other-side-of-early-marriage.aspx";s:7:"attribs";a:0:{}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";}}s:7:"pubDate";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:"data";s:29:"Wed, 17 Jul 2013 14:57:00 GMT";s:7:"attribs";a:0:{}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";}}s:4:"guid";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:"data";s:73:"3100d3ca-1688-42d2-b9b5-d305be013172:6da4c816-84c7-4207-8306-8ea160493b1f";s:7:"attribs";a:1:{s:0:"";a:1:{s:11:"isPermaLink";s:5:"false";}}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";}}s:8:"comments";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:"data";s:115:"http://community.focusonthefamily.com/b/boundless/archive/2013/07/17/the-other-side-of-early-marriage.aspx#comments";s:7:"attribs";a:0:{}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";}}s:11:"description";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:"data";s:5330:"<p class="p1">I always appreciate considering the &quot;other side&quot; of issues.&nbsp;</p>
<p class="p2">If you&#39;ve been reading Boundless for any length of time, you&#39;ve likely read some columns and articles on the benefits of marrying young, such as <a href="http://www.boundless.org/relationships/2010/i-got-married-young-but-not-young-enough-part-1">this one</a> by Heather Koerner, <a href="http://www.boundless.org/relationships/2006/get-married-young-man">this one</a> by Alex Chediak or&nbsp;<a href="http://www.boundless.org/advice/2009/can-you-marry-too-young">this one</a> by Candice Watters.</p>
<p class="p2">In her Her.meneutics guest blog post, &quot;<a href="http://www.christianitytoday.com/women/2013/july/christian-case-against-early-marriage.html">A Christian Case Against Early Marriage,</a>&quot; Ashley Moore brings an opposing perspective &mdash; the other side.</p>
<p class="p2">She contends that Christian singles may be being pressured into marriage relationships for which they aren&#39;t ready &mdash; relationships that may be doomed to failure due to a lack of maturity.</p>
<p class="p2" style="margin-left:30px;">&quot;Sure, plenty of Christian couples marry young and go on to have strong, happy marriages. We can celebrate those well-matched young ones, whether they were especially mature or simply lucky to have found one another. But that doesn&#39;t mean that young marriage should become the biblical model for the church, particularly when we can&#39;t guarantee all will share their fate.</p>
<p class="p4" style="margin-left:30px;">&quot;Immature Christians who marry too early may just find themselves in immature marriages instead of immature singleness. Some women who say &#39;I do&#39; right out of college soon discover that their husbands aren&#39;t adults yet. Lacking work ethic, maturity in faith, and growth may be easy to hide in undergrad, but blaringly obvious in the real world. While the demands of mortgages, bills, and babies, force them to man up, the growing pains that accompany the process may put unnecessary strain on a young marriage.&quot;</p>
<p class="p4">The author admits that older singles do face greater temptation in the area of sexual purity. However, she contends that&#39;s not a good enough reason to enter marriage before one is ready:</p>
<p class="p4" style="margin-left:30px;">&quot;So yes, early-marriage champs, the longer we stayed unmarried, the greater our chances of sexual screwups. You win on that one. But sex isn&#39;t enough to hold up an argument for early marriage (though we hear it <a href="http://www.christianpost.com/news/pastor-stop-delaying-get-married-early-78145/"><span class="s1">again and again</span></a>). Single Christians have the opportunity to throw the curve&mdash;to demonstrate that a life devoted to honoring Christ is in fact possible outside of the binds of marriage.&quot;</p>
<p class="p4">I both agree and disagree with Moore. First of all, I feel she&#39;s being a little too dismissive of the positives of early marriage. (The very publication she&#39;s writing for&nbsp;lauded its benefits in the 2009 article, &quot;<a href="http://www.christianitytoday.com/ct/2009/august/16.22.html">The Case for Early Marriage</a>.&quot;) However, for many singles, early marriage just isn&#39;t going to happen (I married at 31). And when early marriage doesn&#39;t happen for a believer who desires it, I don&#39;t think he or she has to (or should) assume that all hope for a fulfilling marriage is gone.&nbsp;</p>
<p class="p4">While there are certainly good reasons immature 20 year olds shouldn&#39;t tie the knot, the negatives Moore points out for early marriage &mdash; such as immaturity, lack of a work ethic and a weak relationship with Christ &mdash; are not relegated to young people. Paul told young believers to set an example for the church (<a href="http://www.biblegateway.com/passage/?search=1%20Timothy%204:12&amp;version=ESV" target="_blank">1 Timothy 4:12</a>). Just because a person is older does not mean they are wiser &mdash; or more ready for marriage.</p>
<p class="p4">Still, I think the point to be made is that singles should consider whether they are preparing themselves for marriage, whether they are 21 or 41. Marriage requires work, sacrifice and selflessness. But maturity and Christlikeness do not automatically come with a wedding ceremony. They must be cultivated in a believer&#39;s life &mdash; throughout life &mdash; through the work of the Holy Spirit. I&#39;m pro-early marriage, and I&#39;m pro-mature Christian. I don&#39;t think the two need to be mutually exclusive.</p><div style="clear:both;"></div><img src="http://community.focusonthefamily.com/aggbug.aspx?PostID=6122&AppID=8&AppType=Weblog&ContentType=0" width="1" height="1"><div class="feedflare">
