;a:1:{s:8:"origLink";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:"data";s:108:"http://community.focusonthefamily.com/b/boundless/archive/2013/07/04/culture-39-s-sex-story-episode-283.aspx";s:7:"attribs";a:0:{}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";}}}}}i:14;a:6:{s:4:"data";s:0:"";s:7:"attribs";a:0:{}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";s:5:"child";a:5:{s:0:"";a:7:{s:5:"title";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:"data";s:31:"Awkward Christian Dating Advice";s:7:"attribs";a:0:{}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";}}s:4:"link";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:"data";s:101:"http://feedproxy.google.com/~r/boundlessline/blog/~3/mCKwGLPA9mY/awkward-christian-dating-advice.aspx";s:7:"attribs";a:0:{}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";}}s:7:"pubDate";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:"data";s:29:"Wed, 03 Jul 2013 20:30:00 GMT";s:7:"attribs";a:0:{}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";}}s:4:"guid";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:"data";s:73:"3100d3ca-1688-42d2-b9b5-d305be013172:cca38e20-b072-440e-a203-36dd35060d9c";s:7:"attribs";a:1:{s:0:"";a:1:{s:11:"isPermaLink";s:5:"false";}}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";}}s:8:"comments";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:"data";s:114:"http://community.focusonthefamily.com/b/boundless/archive/2013/07/03/awkward-christian-dating-advice.aspx#comments";s:7:"attribs";a:0:{}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";}}s:11:"description";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:"data";s:2973:"<p class="p1">I think this is a good topic (and one <a href="http://community.focusonthefamily.com/b/boundless/archive/2010/07/23/true-tale.aspx">we&#39;ve discussed</a> a few times). I&#39;m talking about the things people say to you when you&#39;re single, and they know (or assume) you&#39;d like to be not-single.&nbsp;</p>
<p class="p2">A guest blogger at Stuff Christians Like, comedian Kristin Weber, recently <a href="http://www.jonacuff.com/stuffchristianslike/2013/05/giving-christian-singles-awkward-advice/">tackled this topic</a>:</p>
<p class="p2" style="margin-left:30px;">I&rsquo;m single, in my late twenties, and live in the Bible Belt. Needless to say, I get some pretty spectacular advice both about being single and how to become <i>un</i>single. At this point, I almost <i>want</i> to stay single so I can keep getting new story material.</p>
<p class="p3">She goes on to share some of the awkward advice she&#39;s received. This was my favorite:</p>
<p class="p3" style="margin-left:30px;">&quot;If you want to get married, you need to hang a pair of men&rsquo;s pants at the end of your bed, and then pray to God every night to fill those pants with the perfect man.&rdquo;</p>
<p class="p4">Yep. That&#39;s pretty awkward.</p>
<p class="p4">Singleness is a <span style="text-decoration:line-through;">problem</span> subject people seem to love to offer advice on. And advice can be a good thing. As Proverbs 12:15 says, &quot;The way of a fool is right in his own eyes, but a wise man listens to advice.&quot;</p>
<p class="p6">But I think most of us have experienced receiving unsolicited (and possibly unwanted) advice that is also unhelpful. It <em>is</em> helpful to remember that the advice-giver usually means well. I remember my younger brother (who married seven years before me and was pretty baffled that I hadn&#39;t hooked a guy) once saying, &quot;Aren&#39;t there, like, any Christian coffee shops you can go to, to meet guys?&quot;&nbsp;</p>
<p class="p6">I nicely said no. No, there were not.&nbsp;</p>
<p class="p6">(Though awkward advice at the time, it&#39;s ironic that I did, in fact, meet my husband at a coffee shop.)</p>
